WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:14.480
I want to start off today by talking a little bit about Minnesota, the land of 10,000 lakes,

00:00:14.480 --> 00:00:16.320
as the locals call it.

00:00:16.320 --> 00:00:23.400
Now, fair call, I, before about a week ago, hadn't actually been anywhere near Minnesota.

00:00:23.400 --> 00:00:26.959
But in spite of that, I do actually know a few things about the state.

00:00:26.959 --> 00:00:31.799
I know that depending on which sources you use, there's actually anywhere between 18

00:00:31.799 --> 00:00:36.400
and 24,000 uniquely registered water bodies across the state.

00:00:36.400 --> 00:00:41.520
I know that of those, there are around about 9,000 which have detailed inspection data

00:00:41.520 --> 00:00:42.860
available for them.

00:00:42.860 --> 00:00:45.740
That's about 4 million acres or so.

00:00:45.740 --> 00:00:51.520
And of those, there's almost 10% of these which are infested with invasive species,

00:00:51.520 --> 00:00:56.520
which is a big problem for the state and the people who enjoy those lakes.

00:00:56.520 --> 00:00:58.320
Maybe let's back up for a second.

00:00:58.320 --> 00:00:59.639
Who is this guy?

00:00:59.639 --> 00:01:03.639
Why is this man from the other side of the world standing here talking about invasive

00:01:03.639 --> 00:01:05.400
species in Minnesota?

00:01:05.400 --> 00:01:07.959
Does he realize he's not in Minnesota right now?

00:01:07.959 --> 00:01:09.879
These are fair questions.

00:01:09.879 --> 00:01:10.879
I'll start off.

00:01:10.879 --> 00:01:11.879
My name is Nick Snellgrove.

00:01:11.879 --> 00:01:13.959
I'm a tech lead at Ippi Interactive.

00:01:13.959 --> 00:01:18.199
We're full service partners for Australia and New Zealand with posit.

00:01:18.199 --> 00:01:24.440
And the reason that I'm standing here right now is because of these four invasive species.

00:01:24.440 --> 00:01:28.900
So for the last four years or so, we've been working with collaborators at the University

00:01:28.900 --> 00:01:33.919
of Minnesota, the Aquatic Invasive Species Research Center, battling these species in

00:01:33.919 --> 00:01:34.919
particular.

00:01:34.919 --> 00:01:41.000
So zebra mussel, starry stonewort, Eurasian watermilfoil, and spiny water flea.

00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:45.160
Now when I say something like battling invasive species, you might be tempted to think of

00:01:45.160 --> 00:01:46.800
something a bit more dramatic.

00:01:46.800 --> 00:01:51.000
It reminds me kind of of the movie Jaws, you know, people out on the boats hunting down

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:53.820
these creatures and bringing them to justice.

00:01:53.820 --> 00:01:58.419
Maybe it is that way for some, but in our case, it's a little bit more subtle.

00:01:58.419 --> 00:02:02.180
The creatures we're battling against are a little bit smaller, so we have to be a little

00:02:02.180 --> 00:02:04.660
bit more detailed.

00:02:04.660 --> 00:02:08.820
So for me, when I'm talking about battling invasive species, I'm actually talking about

00:02:08.820 --> 00:02:13.820
how we're using cloud-based infrastructure and a shiny application called the AIS Explorer.

00:02:13.820 --> 00:02:16.100
And that's what we're going to go over today.

00:02:16.100 --> 00:02:21.460
So in this talk, we're going to be going over how we've built up this cloud-based infrastructure

00:02:21.460 --> 00:02:26.139
around the AIS Explorer to make sure that it's accessible to the people who need it,

00:02:26.139 --> 00:02:31.179
relevant for their uses, and that it performs well so that they can focus on what they need

00:02:31.179 --> 00:02:33.500
to do with it.

00:02:33.500 --> 00:02:36.179
So let's have a little bit of background about this shiny app.

00:02:36.179 --> 00:02:42.419
So this was initially conceptualized back in 2019 with the support of the people at

00:02:42.419 --> 00:02:47.979
the University of Minnesota, and specifically the Minnesota Aquatic Invasive Species Research

00:02:47.979 --> 00:02:48.979
Center.

00:02:48.979 --> 00:02:52.699
We wouldn't be able to do any of this without the support of these people.

00:02:52.699 --> 00:02:57.860
So special call out, thank you to Nick Phelps, Amy Kinsley, and Alex Badges for all their

00:02:57.860 --> 00:02:58.860
support over the years.

00:02:58.860 --> 00:03:00.339
They've been wonderful.

00:03:00.339 --> 00:03:05.300
So the AIS Explorer started its life as a decision support and risk management tool

00:03:05.300 --> 00:03:12.419
to help decision makers on the ground in the state protect their lakes from these invasive

00:03:12.419 --> 00:03:17.259
species by linking up these complex analytics with these practical decisions that they need

00:03:17.300 --> 00:03:20.139
to make day-to-day.

00:03:20.139 --> 00:03:26.580
We finished development of the first version of AIS Explorer back in mid-2020, and it has

00:03:26.580 --> 00:03:31.380
remained in production since then, and it's been actively in use during that time.

00:03:31.380 --> 00:03:34.779
So these decision makers, the county managers, have been using this app.

00:03:34.779 --> 00:03:38.139
It's battle-tested, and it's been through several updates over that time.

00:03:38.139 --> 00:03:42.220
We've continued to maintain it and provide new features for the people who are using

00:03:42.220 --> 00:03:43.220
it.

00:03:43.220 --> 00:03:46.779
And there's some pretty complex stuff going on behind the scenes here.

00:03:47.300 --> 00:03:49.779
Now, I'm not a data scientist.

00:03:49.779 --> 00:03:53.500
My background is in software, so I probably can't tell you a lot about the details of

00:03:53.500 --> 00:03:59.020
these models, but I can tell you that we've linked up these kind of collection of Python

00:03:59.020 --> 00:04:01.300
and R models into the application.

00:04:01.300 --> 00:04:08.979
So briefly, we have a risk model written in Python, which is used to determine the risk

00:04:08.979 --> 00:04:13.100
of lakes becoming infested within the next eight years, I think.

00:04:13.100 --> 00:04:18.739
Then we also have an intervention model, which allows users to kind of produce a simulation

00:04:18.739 --> 00:04:25.660
of if they intervene at certain lakes in certain ways, so things like inspections or decontamination

00:04:25.660 --> 00:04:31.540
or education and outreach, how is that going to change the story for these lakes?

00:04:31.540 --> 00:04:35.739
We have an inspection model, which allows people to determine the most cost-effective

00:04:35.739 --> 00:04:41.579
or the most beneficial way that they can place inspectors around their lakes in a county.

00:04:41.579 --> 00:04:46.739
And then finally, the collaboration model, one of the new additions, which is enabling

00:04:46.739 --> 00:04:52.940
county managers to see how the story changes if they pool their resources together.

00:04:52.940 --> 00:04:56.619
So these models are pretty complicated, and that makes it a bit of a challenging process

00:04:56.619 --> 00:05:02.579
to keep them fed, watered, operating as they need to.

00:05:02.579 --> 00:05:07.779
The source data that feeds these models updates pretty frequently, and the computations which

00:05:07.779 --> 00:05:12.420
happen to produce the results we present in the app are pretty intensive.

00:05:12.420 --> 00:05:14.660
It takes quite a long time.

00:05:14.660 --> 00:05:17.940
We want to make sure that our Shiny app performs well for the people who are using it.

00:05:17.940 --> 00:05:22.339
So we need to kind of address that in the way that we're hosting this app.

00:05:22.339 --> 00:05:26.140
And even if we wanted to go with kind of a manual update process, that's not going to

00:05:26.140 --> 00:05:31.019
be practical for us in this case either, because we don't actually know when these updates

00:05:31.019 --> 00:05:32.260
are going to need to be applied.

00:05:32.260 --> 00:05:35.339
It's a bit of a variable timing on that one.

00:05:35.339 --> 00:05:39.899
So this kind of boils down to three challenges that we have, which is, how do we ensure that

00:05:39.899 --> 00:05:45.500
the AIS Explorer is accessible, relevant, and performant for the people who are using

00:05:45.500 --> 00:05:46.500
it?

00:05:46.500 --> 00:05:48.179
So that's what we'll go over now.

00:05:48.179 --> 00:05:52.299
We're going to start off firstly with accessibility.

00:05:52.299 --> 00:05:56.100
This is how we're making sure that these people can actually use the Shiny app that we've

00:05:56.100 --> 00:05:58.100
built and prepared for them.

00:05:58.100 --> 00:06:01.579
And the first question we ask is, where do we actually host this?

00:06:02.459 --> 00:06:07.380
There's usually a couple of options between, do we host it kind of on-prem on some server

00:06:07.380 --> 00:06:10.940
that we have, or do we host it somewhere in the cloud?

00:06:10.940 --> 00:06:14.899
For obvious reasons, it's probably not going to be great if we host it back in our office

00:06:14.899 --> 00:06:16.019
in Wellington.

00:06:16.019 --> 00:06:19.700
So we decided to go with some cloud infrastructure.

00:06:19.700 --> 00:06:24.660
And some discussions with the folks at Mazark led us to Amazon Web Services.

00:06:24.660 --> 00:06:30.619
Over 200 cloud-based services for us to choose from, 32 different regions, 102 availability

00:06:30.660 --> 00:06:35.739
zones, which means that we can take our application and put it right next door, where it's going

00:06:35.739 --> 00:06:41.739
to be nice and accessible for the folks in Minnesota who need to use it.

00:06:41.739 --> 00:06:48.260
So now that we've decided on AWS, that leads us to the Elastic Compute Cloud, or EC2 instances.

00:06:48.260 --> 00:06:53.779
So these cloud-based servers, which we create one of these and upload the code for our Shiny

00:06:53.779 --> 00:06:56.739
application into one of these instances.

00:06:56.739 --> 00:07:00.220
And from this, we can do a lot of different configurations if we need to.

00:07:00.220 --> 00:07:01.399
We can adjust the performance.

00:07:01.399 --> 00:07:03.459
We can change security groups.

00:07:03.459 --> 00:07:07.459
We can customize these instances however we need to, really.

00:07:07.459 --> 00:07:10.380
We can also pick from a variety of different performance tiers.

00:07:10.380 --> 00:07:16.299
So we can crank up the performance of the application by just picking a different option

00:07:16.299 --> 00:07:20.380
from a dropdown and restarting the server, which can be really helpful, because this

00:07:20.380 --> 00:07:23.420
app can take quite a bit of effort sometimes.

00:07:23.420 --> 00:07:27.420
The other really useful thing about this is that we get to record our backups, and we

00:07:27.619 --> 00:07:32.619
can take kind of a snapshot of the state of these servers using the Amazon machine images,

00:07:32.619 --> 00:07:33.619
these AMIs.

00:07:33.619 --> 00:07:37.179
And they're going to come in handy later as well.

00:07:37.179 --> 00:07:42.019
So we have our Shiny code on this EC2 instance, and then we actually need to have some way

00:07:42.019 --> 00:07:43.779
of running the Shiny app.

00:07:43.779 --> 00:07:48.700
And a little bit of a fun detour we had to take with this one is that we actually run

00:07:48.700 --> 00:07:51.380
the Shiny app directly on this EC2 instance.

00:07:51.380 --> 00:07:57.019
Now traditionally, you would probably go with a Shiny server, but as I painfully found out,

00:07:57.019 --> 00:07:59.940
while we were kind of going through this initial development, there are some edge cases in

00:07:59.940 --> 00:08:05.339
here that come up when you try to throw 18,000 lakes onto a single leaflet map, which meant

00:08:05.339 --> 00:08:08.480
that Shiny server actually wasn't really having it for us.

00:08:08.480 --> 00:08:12.339
So we decided to just run the app directly on the EC2 instance.

00:08:12.339 --> 00:08:16.380
And that brings up some questions, which we'll talk about later, about how we deal with multiple

00:08:16.380 --> 00:08:18.019
users.

00:08:18.019 --> 00:08:22.820
But with these solutions, we've made our app accessible to the people in Minnesota, and

00:08:22.820 --> 00:08:26.140
they can use it, and it should be performing reasonably well.

00:08:26.140 --> 00:08:29.500
The next thing we need to think about is how do we keep this relevant?

00:08:29.500 --> 00:08:33.020
So we've got these four complicated models in here.

00:08:33.020 --> 00:08:37.780
And like I said, I'm not going to go too much into the details of these models, but there's

00:08:37.780 --> 00:08:39.940
a couple of things to call out here.

00:08:39.940 --> 00:08:44.659
So if you have a look at the kind of runtime of these different models, you can see it's

00:08:44.659 --> 00:08:46.500
a pretty variable scale here.

00:08:46.500 --> 00:08:49.820
We've got models which take sort of anywhere from one to five minutes, depending on the

00:08:49.820 --> 00:08:54.219
inputs, up to 20 hours or more.

00:08:54.299 --> 00:08:58.940
So it's a pretty variable range of models and how long it takes for these outputs to

00:08:58.940 --> 00:09:00.059
be produced.

00:09:00.059 --> 00:09:03.219
And all of these need to come into our app at the same time.

00:09:03.219 --> 00:09:07.099
The other thing to call out here is that there's a common thread running between these models,

00:09:07.099 --> 00:09:11.219
which is the source data, which is coming from the DNR infested waters list.

00:09:11.219 --> 00:09:15.700
So this is produced by the Minnesota Department of Natural Resources.

00:09:15.700 --> 00:09:20.539
And basically, this is feeding everything else which we put into the AIS Explorer.

00:09:20.539 --> 00:09:26.659
All of our models depend on this Excel file, which lives on the DNR website.

00:09:26.659 --> 00:09:31.900
So we obviously need to know when this changes, and that's going to be the trigger for us

00:09:31.900 --> 00:09:36.900
to actually run our models again and produce the results that we need.

00:09:36.900 --> 00:09:38.359
Specifically from that, we need two things.

00:09:38.359 --> 00:09:43.859
We need the species that a lake is infested with, and we need the DOW number.

00:09:43.859 --> 00:09:48.940
It's a unique identifier for each water body which is infested in that list.

00:09:49.380 --> 00:09:55.979
I talked earlier about a variable update timing, and that's down to the season.

00:09:55.979 --> 00:10:01.219
So when it's winter in Minnesota, the lakes freeze over, people aren't really inspecting

00:10:01.219 --> 00:10:02.260
all that much.

00:10:02.260 --> 00:10:05.200
So they don't get a lot of new data in this spreadsheet.

00:10:05.200 --> 00:10:10.500
But during the summer, we might be seeing multiple times a week updates to the spreadsheet.

00:10:10.500 --> 00:10:14.580
So we need to have an automated process to know when that's changing.

00:10:14.580 --> 00:10:17.460
And again, for that, we turn to AWS.

00:10:17.460 --> 00:10:25.179
So we're using Lambda to write some serverless code which will check the infested waters

00:10:25.179 --> 00:10:29.979
list and see if there are any changes from the last time we looked at it.

00:10:29.979 --> 00:10:32.260
And if there are no changes, that's great.

00:10:32.260 --> 00:10:33.440
We don't need to worry.

00:10:33.440 --> 00:10:37.640
If there are changes, though, then we need to do something, and we're going to spin up

00:10:37.640 --> 00:10:41.140
a processing instance to actually run these models.

00:10:41.140 --> 00:10:46.179
So we use EventBridge to schedule that rule to run every 12 hours, which is how I've ended

00:10:46.179 --> 00:10:52.820
up having an email inbox which twice a day gives me a notification, has this file changed,

00:10:52.820 --> 00:10:53.820
yes or no?

00:10:53.820 --> 00:10:59.539
Which is great for my mental well-being, but that doesn't matter.

00:10:59.539 --> 00:11:04.020
So if there has been a change, then we spin up a processing instance.

00:11:04.020 --> 00:11:08.739
And this is how we are actually running the model code and producing these outputs that

00:11:08.739 --> 00:11:10.099
we need.

00:11:10.099 --> 00:11:12.380
And it takes a decent amount of time.

00:11:12.380 --> 00:11:17.539
This is probably running anywhere from sort of 36 to 48 hours once we kick it off.

00:11:17.539 --> 00:11:23.500
But we used one of those AMIs, those images which we created earlier, to kind of take

00:11:23.500 --> 00:11:29.260
a copy of a server which contains all of our preprocessing code, and we have a cron job

00:11:29.260 --> 00:11:34.099
on that instance that gets created to kickstart our pipeline process.

00:11:34.099 --> 00:11:39.059
That will run through, and then when everything is completed, we have another script on there

00:11:39.219 --> 00:11:44.020
which will upload all of our results, so the RDS files which are produced, we upload all

00:11:44.020 --> 00:11:49.059
of those to an S3 bucket, and we'll have them then sitting there waiting to be ingested

00:11:49.059 --> 00:11:50.419
by the app.

00:11:50.419 --> 00:11:54.820
So that all happens without even needing to think about it, really.

00:11:54.820 --> 00:11:56.460
But then how do we get it into the app?

00:11:56.460 --> 00:11:58.260
That's the next important question.

00:11:58.260 --> 00:12:05.219
And the way that we do that is on our EC2 instance, which is hosting the Shiny application,

00:12:05.219 --> 00:12:10.820
we have a cron job which, once a day, will go to our S3 bucket, retrieve the latest data

00:12:10.820 --> 00:12:14.859
that's available in there, and then restart the Shiny application.

00:12:14.859 --> 00:12:19.460
And we've got this scheduled for about 5 in the morning Minnesota time, so that hopefully

00:12:19.460 --> 00:12:22.760
nobody's going to be affected when the server restarts.

00:12:22.760 --> 00:12:27.179
And this means that when people come to the application, all of the files that they need

00:12:27.179 --> 00:12:32.780
are already available, loaded in directly from the same server that the application

00:12:32.780 --> 00:12:33.780
is running on.

00:12:33.780 --> 00:12:38.820
So they can get right to what they need to do.

00:12:38.820 --> 00:12:44.140
That brings us around to kind of the last point of these challenges that we need to

00:12:44.140 --> 00:12:48.859
solve, and that's the idea of the performance of the application.

00:12:48.859 --> 00:12:53.099
We've already kind of spoken to some of these points as we've gone along.

00:12:53.099 --> 00:12:57.780
So we've made sure that we're hosting the Shiny app in the right place.

00:12:57.780 --> 00:13:04.099
We've made sure to increase the specs of our EC2 instance to make sure it has kind

00:13:04.099 --> 00:13:08.219
of enough power behind it to run maybe some of the more complicated tasks that we need

00:13:08.219 --> 00:13:13.940
to do in the app, things like presenting all those lakes on a leaflet map.

00:13:13.940 --> 00:13:18.719
We've preprocessed our expensive model outputs so that they're all kind of just sitting there

00:13:18.719 --> 00:13:22.859
ready to go whenever someone comes to the application.

00:13:22.859 --> 00:13:27.059
But the question then is, what else should we do?

00:13:27.059 --> 00:13:31.700
And that kind of comes back to the way that we're running the Shiny app as well.

00:13:31.700 --> 00:13:36.500
So I mentioned before that we're not using Shiny server on these instances because it

00:13:36.500 --> 00:13:40.020
was kind of just a little bit too much in some cases.

00:13:40.020 --> 00:13:45.219
So that means that we kind of need to handle the question of load balancing ourselves.

00:13:45.219 --> 00:13:49.859
So we want to make sure that if there are multiple concurrent users for the app, that

00:13:49.859 --> 00:13:55.020
they're not going to bump into each other and cause problems in terms of their individual

00:13:55.020 --> 00:13:56.020
user experiences.

00:13:56.020 --> 00:14:01.500
And the way that we do that, again, we're turning to AWS, and we're using the load balancer

00:14:01.500 --> 00:14:05.280
along with target groups and autoscaling groups.

00:14:05.280 --> 00:14:09.739
So our load balancer is linked up to the application URL.

00:14:09.739 --> 00:14:15.479
So when someone arrives intending to use the AIS Explorer, instead of just going directly

00:14:15.599 --> 00:14:20.840
to the server which is running the application, they'll instead be directed to the load balancer,

00:14:20.840 --> 00:14:23.479
which we have in the AWS Cloud.

00:14:23.479 --> 00:14:28.000
From there, the load balancer is going to take their connection, and it's going to redirect

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:35.080
them into the target group, which has one of however many instances we have of the AIS

00:14:35.080 --> 00:14:37.119
Explorer at the time.

00:14:37.119 --> 00:14:41.640
And so it's going to distribute that traffic into the target group, depending on how it's

00:14:41.679 --> 00:14:46.599
currently being used and how that load is currently shared across the instances in that

00:14:46.599 --> 00:14:48.479
target group.

00:14:48.479 --> 00:14:53.320
In terms of how many instances we have in that target group, we use the autoscaling

00:14:53.320 --> 00:14:55.919
group to kind of control that for us.

00:14:55.919 --> 00:14:58.039
So we have a minimum number of instances.

00:14:58.039 --> 00:15:00.159
So we always have at least one running.

00:15:00.159 --> 00:15:04.440
And then we have a certain threshold, which if the traffic on that instance gets to a

00:15:04.440 --> 00:15:11.599
certain point, then we'll spin up a new instance automatically so that as new people arrive,

00:15:11.599 --> 00:15:13.000
they will be redirected.

00:15:13.000 --> 00:15:17.059
Instead of going onto the same instance, they'll end up on one of the new ones, and it'll kind

00:15:17.059 --> 00:15:25.760
of share that load out so that people aren't really all crammed into one specific server.

00:15:25.760 --> 00:15:31.159
And as it kind of automatically creates these instances, as that traffic dies down, it will

00:15:31.159 --> 00:15:35.960
also safely tear those down without causing any problems for people who may be using the

00:15:35.960 --> 00:15:38.719
app.

00:15:38.719 --> 00:15:43.760
So besides the load balancing, there's one other thing which we want to briefly consider,

00:15:43.760 --> 00:15:45.440
which is around performance tuning.

00:15:45.440 --> 00:15:46.719
And we've already done some of this.

00:15:46.719 --> 00:15:50.039
We want to make sure we're doing as little in the Shiny app as we can.

00:15:50.039 --> 00:15:52.340
We've preprocessed our expensive operations.

00:15:52.340 --> 00:15:54.859
We cache our results in the Shiny app.

00:15:54.859 --> 00:15:59.400
So using functions like bind cache in the app to kind of hold on to expensive operations

00:15:59.400 --> 00:16:01.320
people may have already done.

00:16:01.320 --> 00:16:06.760
But the last question which comes up for me is, what if we need to run one of our expensive

00:16:06.760 --> 00:16:07.760
models?

00:16:07.799 --> 00:16:13.039
So to answer that, we actually went a little bit outside of AWS.

00:16:13.039 --> 00:16:18.520
It kind of crosses over a bit, but we have, on another EC2 instance, we have OpenCPU installed.

00:16:18.520 --> 00:16:23.760
And we've taken, in this case, the intervention model, and we've put that into OpenCPU as

00:16:23.760 --> 00:16:28.719
a package, which then allows us to, when someone is trying to run one of these intervention

00:16:28.719 --> 00:16:32.919
models, instead of having them sitting there waiting for 10 minutes while the model runs

00:16:32.919 --> 00:16:37.679
and the report generates, we actually let them send this request and then continue using

00:16:37.679 --> 00:16:43.239
the app while OpenCPU in the background on a different server is actually working on

00:16:43.239 --> 00:16:44.400
that request.

00:16:44.400 --> 00:16:51.179
And when it's done, we email the results as a report to the person who initially made

00:16:51.179 --> 00:16:52.440
that request.

00:16:52.440 --> 00:16:54.340
So it's a very hands-off approach.

00:16:54.340 --> 00:16:59.000
And that allows people to use these expensive models without needing to kind of sit around

00:16:59.000 --> 00:17:02.479
and wait for the results.

00:17:02.479 --> 00:17:09.119
So using these cloud services, we've taken our Shiny application and we've made it accessible

00:17:09.119 --> 00:17:10.979
to the people who need it most.

00:17:10.979 --> 00:17:15.680
We have made sure that it is relevant, so it's always kept as up-to-date as possible

00:17:15.680 --> 00:17:20.800
so that the decision makers on the ground can make well-informed decisions about the

00:17:20.800 --> 00:17:23.359
ways that they're managing these species.

00:17:23.359 --> 00:17:28.479
And we've made sure that it performs well so that people don't have to waste time and

00:17:28.479 --> 00:17:31.439
wait around for the results that they want to see.

00:17:31.439 --> 00:17:37.280
They can focus more on making informed decisions and kind of taking that to battle these invasive

00:17:37.280 --> 00:17:38.680
species.

00:17:38.680 --> 00:17:42.160
We never really win the fight against these invasive species.

00:17:42.160 --> 00:17:43.959
We just keep on fighting them.

00:17:43.959 --> 00:17:50.719
And because of these services we've introduced, the AIS Explorer is and will remain a very

00:17:50.719 --> 00:17:56.680
effective tool in the fight against those species now and in the future.

00:17:56.680 --> 00:17:57.680
Thank you.

00:17:57.680 --> 00:18:06.479
Thank you so much, Nicholas.

00:18:06.479 --> 00:18:08.040
We have a few questions.

00:18:08.040 --> 00:18:13.400
I'll probably take a few, but if you have more, feel free to ask Nicholas maybe outside

00:18:13.400 --> 00:18:14.400
after this talk.

00:18:14.400 --> 00:18:19.599
So the first question is, do you use an Amazon AMI or how do you get the latest version of

00:18:19.599 --> 00:18:21.520
R onto your EC2?

00:18:21.520 --> 00:18:26.319
So do we use the AMI?

00:18:26.319 --> 00:18:27.319
Correct.

00:18:27.959 --> 00:18:31.000
Yeah, so we have these AMIs set up.

00:18:31.000 --> 00:18:36.119
So we have one set up for the instance which actually holds the Shiny app.

00:18:36.119 --> 00:18:42.040
And then we also have one set up for the instance which contains kind of our processing code.

00:18:42.040 --> 00:18:46.719
So there's kind of two of those which we are mainly using.

00:18:46.719 --> 00:18:51.760
And we have kind of other services that we then use to get those going.

00:18:51.760 --> 00:18:56.640
But actually creating them is kind of a manual process as we're going through development.

00:18:56.959 --> 00:19:02.280
So whenever we do a round of updates or we did an update recently, we introduced some

00:19:02.280 --> 00:19:03.280
new models.

00:19:03.280 --> 00:19:05.719
And as we were doing that, we uploaded some new code.

00:19:05.719 --> 00:19:10.079
We updated kind of the dependencies, the other packages we were using, and kind of just created

00:19:10.079 --> 00:19:11.640
a new image from that.

00:19:11.640 --> 00:19:17.819
So yeah, as we're going through our development process, we actually use one of those instances.

00:19:17.819 --> 00:19:23.040
We have like a development instance which we have running just kind of in the background.

00:19:23.040 --> 00:19:29.160
And we kind of take that and then we'll gradually switch that over to be our new template for

00:19:29.160 --> 00:19:30.160
the production version.

00:19:30.160 --> 00:19:31.760
Does that make sense?

00:19:31.760 --> 00:19:32.760
Awesome.

00:19:32.760 --> 00:19:33.760
Thank you so much.

00:19:33.760 --> 00:19:36.000
Hopefully this is a quick one.

